1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:06,838
You're listening to: The Cache Stampede That Took Down Our API: A Redis p99 War Story.

2
00:00:06,838 --> 00:00:16,935
A single expiring Redis key sent 4,000 requests to PostgreSQL at once and spiked our p99 latency to 9 seconds.

3
00:00:16,935 --> 00:00:24,591
Here's how cache stampedes happen, how we debugged ours, and the locking + jitter fixes that cut p99 by 80%.

4
00:00:24,591 --> 00:00:25,625
Let's get started.

5
00:00:25,625 --> 00:00:31,430
At 9:00 AM sharp, our patient-portal API would fall over for about thirty seconds.

6
00:00:31,430 --> 00:00:32,608
Every single morning.

7
00:00:32,608 --> 00:00:40,685
Dashboards green at 8:59, p99 latency at 9 seconds at 9:00, back to normal by 9:01.

8
00:00:40,685 --> 00:00:45,817
No deploy, no traffic spike that explained it, no error in the application logs.

9
00:00:45,817 --> 00:00:48,076
Just a daily, punctual brownout.

10
00:00:48,076 --> 00:00:54,026
It took me two days to understand that the cause was a caching feature we had added to make things faster.

11
00:00:54,026 --> 00:01:02,668
This is the story of a cache stampede — what it is, why it is so easy to cause by accident, and the three fixes that finally killed it.

12
00:01:02,668 --> 00:01:09,579
If you want the foundational patterns first, my Redis caching strategies guide covers the basics this post assumes.

13
00:01:09,579 --> 00:01:13,269
Now, let's talk about The setup: a "fast" dashboard endpoint.

14
00:01:13,269 --> 00:01:17,692
The endpoint was /api/dashboard/summary.

15
00:01:17,692 --> 00:01:27,367
It ran a heavy aggregation across several tables — roughly 400ms of PostgreSQL work — so we cached the result in Redis:

16
00:01:27,367 --> 00:01:28,894
Textbook cache-aside.

17
00:01:28,894 --> 00:01:30,276
It worked beautifully.

18
00:01:30,276 --> 00:01:34,603
p50 dropped from 400ms to 4ms.

19
00:01:34,603 --> 00:01:36,262
We shipped it and moved on.

20
00:01:36,262 --> 00:01:41,105
The bug is hiding in plain sight, and it only shows itself under concurrency.

21
00:01:41,105 --> 00:01:43,774
Moving on to What actually happened at 9:00 AM.

22
00:01:43,774 --> 00:01:47,524
Our largest customer's staff all log in at 9:00 AM.

23
00:01:47,524 --> 00:01:54,218
The first dashboard load of the day populated the cache with ex=3600 — a one-hour TTL.

24
00:01:54,218 --> 00:01:56,538
One hour later, at 10:00...

25
00:01:56,538 --> 00:01:57,403
no, wait.

26
00:01:57,403 --> 00:02:01,754
The cache had been seeded by a cron job at 8:00 AM during a warmup.

27
00:02:01,754 --> 00:02:07,199
So it expired at exactly 9:00 AM, right as 4,000 users hit the portal.

28
00:02:07,199 --> 00:02:09,951
Here is the failure, step by step:

29
00:02:09,951 --> 00:02:13,834
At 9:00:00, the key summary:42 expires..

30
00:02:13,834 --> 00:02:19,651
Request A arrives, misses the cache, starts the 400ms aggregation..

31
00:02:19,651 --> 00:02:30,396
While A is still running, requests B through D (thousands of them) also arrive, also miss the cache, and also start their own 400ms aggregations..

32
00:02:30,396 --> 00:02:36,286
PostgreSQL now has thousands of identical, expensive queries running at once.

33
00:02:36,286 --> 00:02:38,052
Connection pool exhausted.

34
00:02:38,052 --> 00:02:39,146
Queries queue.

35
00:02:39,146 --> 00:02:44,194
Each one now takes 8–9 seconds instead of 400ms..

36
00:02:44,194 --> 00:02:49,735
Eventually one finishes and repopulates the cache; the stampede subsides..

37
00:02:49,735 --> 00:03:01,201
This is a cache stampede (also called a "thundering herd" or "dog-piling"): when a hot key expires, every concurrent request misses simultaneously and stampedes the origin.

38
00:03:01,201 --> 00:03:07,223
The cache, the thing meant to protect the database, becomes a synchronized trigger that hammers it.

39
00:03:07,223 --> 00:03:10,985
The reason it was invisible in application logs: nothing errored.

40
00:03:10,985 --> 00:03:13,689
Every request eventually succeeded.

41
00:03:13,689 --> 00:03:21,418
The only symptom was latency, which is exactly why you need percentile latency metrics, not just error rates and averages.

42
00:03:21,418 --> 00:03:25,276
An average hides a stampede; p99 screams about it.

43
00:03:25,276 --> 00:03:27,884
Next up: Confirming the diagnosis.

44
00:03:27,884 --> 00:03:29,735
Two signals made it certain:

45
00:03:29,735 --> 00:03:36,670
PostgreSQL pg_stat_activity at 9:00 AM showed dozens of identical SELECT ...

46
00:03:36,670 --> 00:03:40,144
GROUP BY queries all in active state — the smoking gun.

47
00:03:40,144 --> 00:03:45,576
(This is also how I diagnosed an unrelated outage in the connection-pooling war story.).

48
00:03:45,576 --> 00:03:55,444
Redis MONITOR (briefly, never in prod for long) showed a burst of GET summary:42 returning nil, followed much later by a single SET..

49
00:03:55,444 --> 00:03:57,524
The fix is not "cache harder."

50
00:03:57,524 --> 00:04:05,060
It is to make sure that when a hot key is cold, exactly one request rebuilds it while everyone else waits or serves stale.

51
00:04:05,060 --> 00:04:08,870
Let's explore Fix 1: A rebuild lock (single-flight).

52
00:04:08,870 --> 00:04:14,314
The core idea: the first request to miss acquires a short-lived lock and does the rebuild.

53
00:04:14,314 --> 00:04:19,663
Concurrent requests that fail to get the lock wait briefly and then read the freshly-set value.

54
00:04:19,663 --> 00:04:25,096
Now, instead of 4,000 queries, the stampede produces exactly one.

55
00:04:25,096 --> 00:04:28,605
That alone took p99 from 9s back under 1s.

56
00:04:28,605 --> 00:04:32,307
Now let's look at Fix 2: Serve stale while revalidating.

57
00:04:32,354 --> 00:04:38,529
Making thousands of users wait for a rebuild is better than crashing, but it is still a latency hit.

58
00:04:38,529 --> 00:04:47,039
The better pattern is stale-while-revalidate: store the value with a logical "fresh until" timestamp and a longer physical TTL.

59
00:04:47,039 --> 00:04:52,267
Serve the slightly-stale value instantly while one background task refreshes it.

60
00:04:52,267 --> 00:04:56,186
With this, a TTL boundary is no longer a cliff.

61
00:04:56,186 --> 00:05:03,710
Users always get an instant response; the data is at most a few seconds old, which for a dashboard is completely fine.

62
00:05:03,710 --> 00:05:07,243
The expensive rebuild happens off the request path.

63
00:05:07,243 --> 00:05:12,532
Now, let's talk about Fix 3: TTL jitter (stop synchronizing expirations).

64
00:05:12,532 --> 00:05:20,176
The root trigger was that one warmup job set thousands of keys with the same TTL, so they all expired at the same instant.

65
00:05:20,176 --> 00:05:24,154
Even with locking, synchronized expiry concentrates load.

66
00:05:24,154 --> 00:05:28,361
The fix is one line — add randomness to every TTL:

67
00:05:28,361 --> 00:05:35,597
Spreading expirations across a window turns a synchronized spike into a smooth trickle of background refreshes.

68
00:05:35,597 --> 00:05:42,676
This is the cheapest, highest-leverage fix of the three, and I now apply it to every cache set by default.

69
00:05:42,676 --> 00:05:44,203
Moving on to The results.

70
00:05:44,203 --> 00:05:46,090
Metric, Before, After.

71
00:05:46,090 --> 00:05:51,498
p50 latency (9 AM), 400ms, 4ms.

72
00:05:51,498 --> 00:06:00,669
p99 latency (9 AM), 9,000ms, ~1,200ms → with SWR, ~180ms.

73
00:06:00,669 --> 00:06:05,188
Concurrent DB queries at TTL boundary, thousands, 1.

74
00:06:05,188 --> 00:06:07,364
Morning brownouts, daily, gone.

75
00:06:07,364 --> 00:06:18,433
The combination — single-flight locking, serve-stale-while-revalidate, and TTL jitter — cut p99 by roughly 80% and ended the daily 9 AM outage permanently.

76
00:06:18,433 --> 00:06:20,597
Next up: Lessons I took away.

77
00:06:20,597 --> 00:06:23,782
A cache is a load amplifier at its boundaries.

78
00:06:23,782 --> 00:06:28,289
It smooths traffic until a hot key expires, and then it concentrates it.

79
00:06:28,289 --> 00:06:30,356
Design for the miss, not the hit..

80
00:06:30,356 --> 00:06:31,919
Measure percentiles.

81
00:06:31,919 --> 00:06:34,912
Averages and error rates both said "fine."

82
00:06:34,912 --> 00:06:37,676
Only p99 revealed the stampede.

83
00:06:37,676 --> 00:06:41,763
Wire up p95/p99 before you need them..

84
00:06:41,763 --> 00:06:44,070
Jitter everything with a TTL.

85
00:06:44,070 --> 00:06:48,037
Synchronized expirations are a self-inflicted thundering herd..

86
00:06:48,037 --> 00:06:49,743
Prefer stale to slow.

87
00:06:49,743 --> 00:06:58,121
For most read-heavy endpoints, a 3-second-old answer served in 4ms beats a fresh answer served in 9 seconds..

88
00:06:58,121 --> 00:07:11,090
If you are building on Redis, pair this with the fundamentals in Redis caching strategies, and watch your database the way I describe in database connection pooling — stampedes and pool exhaustion are two faces of the same problem.

89
00:07:11,090 --> 00:07:15,296
